                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Mutual Guarantee (Locarno)/830:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-21T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 21, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 21—9:15
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>422. My 407, October 9, noon.<note n="16a" xml:id="d282fn16a">Not printed.</note>
                    The Italian reply to the British proposals with regard to a meeting of the
                    Locarno Powers has been handed to the British Ambassador. Its contents have not
                    been made public. In reply to my inquiry of my British colleague Drummond told
                    me that it was couched in friendly language but expressed Italy’s desire for a
                    return to the original Locarno undertaking rather than the adoption of two
                    agreements of mutual guarantees as proposed by his Government. Drummond was of
                    the opinion that the Italian reply would be a disappointment to London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
